revision.text:
{{Original research|date=January 2011}}
'''Temples and Shrines''' (寺社, Jisha) is a collective term in Japan referring to both {{ill|temples|en|寺院}} and {{ill|shrines|en|神社}}. It is also called '''Shrines and Temples''' (社寺, Shaji) or '''Shrines and Temple Precincts''' (神社仏閣, Jinja Bukkaku).

The term "Jisha" reflects the idea of Buddhist supremacy over Shinto that prevailed until the {{ill|Edo period|en|江戸時代}}. On the other hand, the term "Shaji" appeared as early as the {{ill|Heian period|en|平安時代}}, primarily reflecting a preference for shrines and was widely used after the {{ill|Meiji period|en|明治時代}}.

== Syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism ==

Both temples and shrines (and their deities, {{ill|kami|en|神}} and {{ill|Buddhas|en|仏}}) have been objects of faith in Japan, and prior to the {{ill|separation of Shinto and Buddhism|en|神仏分離}} during the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|en|明治維新}}, they were often treated collectively without distinction when not necessary.

The history of {{ill|syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism|en|神仏習合}} lies in the blending of native {{ill|Shinto|en|神道}} beliefs and imported {{ill|Buddhism|en|仏教}} (especially {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|en|密教}}), which gave rise to diverse faiths like {{ill|Shugendō|en|修験道}}. Theoretical frameworks like the {{ill|honji suijaku|en|本地垂迹}} doctrine attempted to unify these practices, with "Gongen" (権現) serving as an ambiguous term representing both. Examples of architectural integration include "Jingūji" (神宮寺, Shrine-Temples).

During the Meiji period's separation policies, syncretized entities were forcibly divided into either shrines or temples, often resulting in the abolition of one side. 

However, at the grassroots level, these changes caused minimal shifts in popular consciousness. Local {{ill|folk religions|en|民間信仰}} and {{ill|festivals|en|祭り}} continued relatively unchanged, preserving traditions beyond the scope of {{ill|State Shinto|en|国家神道}}.

In modern times, the differences between temples and shrines are seldom emphasized outside specific rituals like funerals. Japanese people are often described as having a "weak sense of faith," with temples and shrines viewed more for their {{ill|worldly benefits|en|現世利益}} or as {{ill|tourist destinations|en|観光地}}.

== Related Topics ==
* {{ill|Syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism|en|神仏習合}}
* {{ill|Temple and Shrine Authorities|en|寺社勢力}}
* {{ill|Magistrates for Temples and Shrines|en|寺社奉行}}
* {{ill|Haibutsu Kishaku|en|廃仏毀釈}}
* {{ill|List of Temples in Japan|en|日本の寺院一覧}}
* {{ill|List of Shrines in Japan|en|神社一覧}}

