The history of {{ill|syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏習合}} lies in the blending of native {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道}} beliefs and imported {{ill|Buddhism|ja|仏教}} (especially {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|ja|密教}}), which gave rise to diverse faiths like {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道}}. Theoretical frameworks like the {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹}} doctrine attempted to unify these practices, with "Gongen" (権現) serving as an ambiguous term representing both. Examples of architectural integration include "Jingūji" (神宮寺, Shrine-Temples).

During the Meiji period's separation policies, syncretized entities were forcibly divided into either shrines or temples, often resulting in the abolition of one side. 

However, at the grassroots level, these changes caused minimal shifts in popular consciousness. Local {{ill|folk religions|ja|民間信仰}} and {{ill|festivals|ja|祭り}} continued relatively unchanged, preserving traditions beyond the scope of {{ill|State Shinto|ja|国家神道}}.

In modern times, the differences between temples and shrines are seldom emphasized outside specific rituals like funerals. Japanese people are often described as having a "weak sense of faith," with temples and shrines viewed more for their {{ill|worldly benefits|ja|現世利益}} or as {{ill|tourist destinations|ja|観光地}}.

