{{ill|Temple and Shrine Regulations|ja|寺社法度|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple and Shrine Regulations|qq=}}
Temple Regulations were a set of legal codes used by the Edo shogunate and local lords to govern religious institutions. These laws often granted temple and shrine lands while imposing various controls, such as restrictions on logging within temple and shrine precincts.

{{ill|Temple and Shrine Restoration Laws|ja|寺社興行法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple and Shrine Restoration Laws|qq=}}
The Temple and Shrine Restoration Laws refer to legal measures implemented by secular authorities to restore and regulate religious ceremonies. These laws aimed to revive religious practices that had declined due to various circumstances, particularly from the late Heian period onward.

{{ill|Temple and Shrine Law|ja|寺社法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple and Shrine Law|qq=}} Temple Law, also known as Temple and Shrine Law, refers to the legal framework governing religious institutions in premodern Japan. This framework involved two main types of authority: secular control over religious institutions and self-regulation by the religious communities themselves.
